<p><b>Bioethics</b> is the philosophical study of the <a href="/wiki/Ethics" title="Ethics">ethical</a> controversies brought about by advances in <a href="/wiki/Biology" title="Biology">biology</a> and <a href="/wiki/Medicine" title="Medicine">medicine</a>. Bioethicists are concerned with the ethical questions that arise in the relationships among <a href="/wiki/Life_sciences" title="Life sciences" class="mw-redirect">life sciences</a>, <a href="/wiki/Biotechnology" title="Biotechnology">biotechnology</a>, <a href="/wiki/Medicine" title="Medicine">medicine</a>, <a href="/wiki/Politics" title="Politics">politics</a>, <a href="/wiki/Law" title="Law">law</a>, <a href="/wiki/Philosophy" title="Philosophy">philosophy</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Theology" title="Theology">theology</a>.</p>
